<p>Another astonishing work, <a href="https://sanskritdocuments.org/doc_z_misc_general/raamakrshhna.pdf">‡§∞‡§æ‡§Æ‡§ï‡•É‡§∑‡•ç‡§£‡§µ‡§ø‡§≤‡•ã‡§Æ‡§ï‡§æ‡§µ‡•ç‡§Ø‡§Æ‡•ç</a> has 36 verses, all with their second lines being the reverse of their first! What‚Äôs amazing is that the first lines speak of <em>Rama</em> and the second ones are of <em>Krishna</em>! It starts with</p>

<blockquote style="text-align:center">
  <h3 id="‡§§‡§æ‡§Ç-‡§≠‡•Ç‡§∏‡•Å‡§§‡§æ-‡§Æ‡•Å‡§ï‡•ç‡§§‡§ø-‡§Æ‡•Å‡§¶‡§æ‡§∞‡§π‡§æ‡§∏‡§Ç-‡§µ‡§Ç‡§¶‡•á‡§Ø‡§§‡•ã-‡§≠‡§µ‡•ç‡§Ø-‡§≠‡§µ‡§Ç-‡§¶‡§Ø‡§æ‡§∂‡•ç‡§∞‡•Ä-">‡§§‡§æ‡§Ç ‡§≠‡•Ç‡§∏‡•Å‡§§‡§æ ‡§Æ‡•Å‡§ï‡•ç‡§§‡§ø ‡§Æ‡•Å‡§¶‡§æ‡§∞‡§π‡§æ‡§∏‡§Ç ‡§µ‡§Ç‡§¶‡•á‡§Ø‡§§‡•ã ‡§≠‡§µ‡•ç‡§Ø ‡§≠‡§µ‡§Ç ‡§¶‡§Ø‡§æ‡§∂‡•ç‡§∞‡•Ä: ‡•§</h3>

  <p>I pray to <em>Rama</em>, who rescued Sita from captivity, who has a majestic laugh, who is kind and who is an incarnation of <em>Vishnu</em>!</p>
</blockquote>

<p>And the second in reverse, reads:</p>
<blockquote class="rkAnuloma">
  <h3 id="‡§∂‡•ç‡§∞‡•Ä-‡§Ø‡§æ‡§¶‡§µ‡§Ç-‡§≠‡§µ‡•ç‡§Ø-‡§≠‡§§‡•ã‡§Ø-‡§¶‡•á‡§µ‡§Ç-‡§∏‡§Ç‡§π‡§æ‡§∞‡§¶‡§æ‡§Æ‡•Å‡§ï‡•ç‡§§‡§ø-‡§Æ‡•Å‡§§‡§æ-‡§∏‡•Å‡§≠‡•Ç‡§§‡§æ‡§Ç-">‡§∂‡•ç‡§∞‡•Ä ‡§Ø‡§æ‡§¶‡§µ‡§Ç ‡§≠‡§µ‡•ç‡§Ø ‡§≠‡§§‡•ã‡§Ø ‡§¶‡•á‡§µ‡§Ç ‡§∏‡§Ç‡§π‡§æ‡§∞‡§¶‡§æ‡§Æ‡•Å‡§ï‡•ç‡§§‡§ø ‡§Æ‡•Å‡§§‡§æ ‡§∏‡•Å‡§≠‡•Ç‡§§‡§æ‡§Ç ‡••</h3>

  <p>I pray to <em>Krishna</em>, who shines with the Sun and the Moon as his eyes, who liberated <em>Putana</em> by killing her.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>A similar work <a href="https://sa.wikisource.org/wiki/%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%98%E0%A4%B5%E0%A4%AF%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%A6%E0%A4%B5%E0%A5%80%E0%A4%AF%E0%A4%AE%E0%A5%8D">‡§∞‡§æ‡§ò‡§µ‡§Ø‡§æ‡§¶‡§µ‡•Ä‡§Ø‡§Æ‡•ç</a>, composed by <em>Sri Venkatadhvari</em> in the 17th century, has 30 such verses, with each verse read differently talks about <em>Rama</em> &amp; <em>Krishna</em>!</p>

<h3 id="guarded-from-all-sides-‡§∏‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§µ‡§§‡•ã‡§≠‡§¶‡•ç‡§∞">Guarded from all sides: ‡§∏‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§µ‡§§‡•ã‡§≠‡§¶‡•ç‡§∞</h3>
<p>Let‚Äôs look another seemingly simple verse from KirƒÅtƒÅrjunƒ´yam (15.25)</p>

<blockquote style="text-align:center">
  <h3 id="‡§¶‡•á‡§µ‡§æ‡§ï‡§æ‡§®‡§ø‡§®‡§ø-‡§ï‡§æ‡§µ‡§æ‡§¶‡•á">‡§¶‡•á‡§µ‡§æ‡§ï‡§æ‡§®‡§ø‡§®‡§ø ‡§ï‡§æ‡§µ‡§æ‡§¶‡•á</h3>
  <h3 id="‡§µ‡§æ‡§π‡§ø‡§ï‡§æ‡§∏‡•ç‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§µ‡§ï‡§æ‡§π‡§ø-‡§µ‡§æ-">‡§µ‡§æ‡§π‡§ø‡§ï‡§æ‡§∏‡•ç‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§µ‡§ï‡§æ‡§π‡§ø ‡§µ‡§æ ‡•§</h3>
  <h3 id="‡§ï‡§æ‡§ï‡§æ‡§∞‡•á‡§≠‡§≠‡§∞‡•á-‡§ï‡§æ-‡§ï‡§æ">‡§ï‡§æ‡§ï‡§æ‡§∞‡•á‡§≠‡§≠‡§∞‡•á ‡§ï‡§æ ‡§ï‡§æ</h3>
  <h3 id="‡§®‡§ø‡§∏‡•ç‡§µ‡§≠‡§µ‡•ç‡§Ø‡§µ‡•ç‡§Ø‡§≠‡§∏‡•ç‡§µ‡§®‡§ø-">‡§®‡§ø‡§∏‡•ç‡§µ‡§≠‡§µ‡•ç‡§Ø‡§µ‡•ç‡§Ø‡§≠‡§∏‡•ç‡§µ‡§®‡§ø ‡••</h3>
  <p><em>O man who desires war! This is that battlefield which excites even the gods, where the battle is not of words. Here people fight and stake their lives not for themselves but for others. This field is full of herds of maddened elephants. Here those who are eager for battle and even those who are not very eager, have to fight.</em></p>
</blockquote>
<p>This extends the symmetry to another dimension, where it‚Äôs symmetrical not just horizontally but also vertically.</p>

